76561198057109145,Recommended,305960,18405996,"Posted: 9 October, 2015",all,Misteragamer,"**Updated 4-1-16**The last time i played this game was 11-7-14. At that time it was little better than a tech demo.I have redownloaded the game. This is my new impressions.I'm going to compare what was, to what is now:(Note, i played on ""good"" setting for graphics).The UI prior - Seem to be well made for the starting screen where you pick your dragon/map and hit the play button. The background was equally nice. Over all, I liked it. When picking your dragon you could look at stats and what could be skills/powers. Detailed, very easy to read. This alone I'd say was very well put together and awesome at that.The UI now - The starting screen where you pick your dragon. First impression... Green neon grass/ground. Picking your dragon button over lapped the play button so all you can see of play is LAY. Which is fine since you can put together that it is a play button. Picking dragons, the details of the dragons you can pick from are lost on the right side fo the screen into the neon green color. Leaving you guessing as to what it is saying.. I think i saw the word Ox for one of the dragons.. not sure what that would be.. maybe fav food? Really not sure what happened here. Hard to read, buttons over lapping. Step down from last time i played. Real disappointment. Almost feels like they went backwards here.Map prior - poorly put together, could tell it was either rushed, or someone new to map making had put it together. Lots of seems where you could see the parts that were put together. Things would randomly fall through or if they walked into a seam, they'd fall through. Going too far in one direction would unload the map from where you were. Once unloaded, the map wouldn't reload. You were left with ""dead zones"" where you couldn't go back to them. Few trees. Villagers and their homes were bunched together like small villages (this is a plus). Over all, really drove home the feel that the game was a Tech Demo.Map Now - Improved, smooth, no seams, nothing falling through the floor. Map doesn't unload and fail to load again when you come back. Rather odd coloring, kind of a neon green or off green for the ""grass"". More trees. Trees look nicer now. Villagers do not appear to live very close together. Takes away from the feel of villages. Over all, makes the game feel like an Alpha so a step up for sure.Mobs prior - Few villagers, chicks with swords and guys with pitch forks (and of course the villager of doom, but he was a bug/glitch), cyclops, wolves, ents (or where they giants?). AI wasn't that good, simple see and attack. Passive mobs, cows, sheep. Easy to kill.Mobs now - Same types of villagers, plus man at arms (or what i'd call them since they had shields), Didn't play long enough to find many other types of mobs. But i did take note there are now deer, and rabbits. Wolves are still in. AI is still rather basic. Though now they don't all attack on sight (but should in cases like the wolves who sat there and let me fry them for one of the quests)Dragon Prior - Going to be honest here. The dragon we had access to when i first played was awesome looking. Really made me think Dragon. Handled ok, would go lopsided every once in a while. Could even change it's face a little.Dragon now - While it does offer i think premade dragons? Not sure as it wouldn't let me actually pick anything. I was able to change the color of my dragon with sliders. Didn't have that option prior. You could make a pink dragon if you wanted to now. However, the body of the dragon as well as head leave me thinking lizard then dragon. They did it the right way the first time. Though to be fair, i heard we'll be able to have more control over what our dragons look like... hopefully. Otherwise I'd say a step backwards here with the shape.Quests prior - there were zero quests.Quests now - very simple quests at first. I didn't put a lot of time in this time around, but i get the feeling the questions are going to become more and more involved.Combat prior - We had claw/fire to use for weapons. Pretty simple to be honest. shoot some fire, or hit them with your claws. I never found any bugs or problems with it when i played then.Combat now - Able to use fire or a tail whip. Tail whip doesn't always seem to hit. Fire will fly off into the distance and cross the map. I found this out by ranging in the direction i had sent some flames doing the quest to find a chest. Actually seems more buggy then it did prior.Over all prior - I felt the game was a tech demo and nothing more. I wouldn't have recommended the game to anyone, but didn't want to leave a poor review as it's not a finished game. I wanted to wait until the game is finished, then give it a real review that may or may not be positive.Over all now - I don't feel like the game is a tech demo anymore. If i were to gage it's ""age"", i'd say it's early to mid Alpha. It's gettingn a lot of factors together now. The map is for sure cleaned up. Just needs more TLC. Combat and UI needs some heavy work. The game does though seem to flow better. There are some real possibilities for this game if it ever gets finished.Do I recommend the game? My answer is still sadly no. Not because it's an early Alpha after 1.5 yrs. Nor because of the remaining bugs, and unfinshed features. It's not even the snails pace it seems this game is being developed at. The reason why I am not willing to recommend this game is simple. Commuication. The developers made a promise to maintain that with us. They failed to keep their promise. I will not move my recommend to a not. Because the game is not finished. As such, there is still a chance the dev's will turn it around yet again. But we'll see how that goes. I will be uninstalling the game now. I'll load it up again when there appears to be either some heavy updates or the game is finished or in another 1.5 years ;) Which ever comes first.**old review**First, I am not recommending that anyone buy this game.I am putting it as a recommend as there is no middle choice. Right now i'm waiting to see where the game goes.The idea of the game.. oh my god, it's awesome, what it could be is fantastic... but fantasy and reality don't go hand in hand. What will come out of this game is by far not set in stone yet.Currently the game play is little better than a tech demo of a game. Bug filled, not very pretty graphic wise and lacking in content. You can fly around as a dragon, and haphazardly attack things with either fire, or melee. You can fly, and burn stuff. That is what is currently available in the game, plus bugs, lots of bugs, tons of bugs, map disappearing and not reloading, suddenly flying with a tilt, etc.To be perfectly honest here. Only buy this game if you want to support the dev's and take a change on if this game will go anywhere or not. It's been out since Nov 7th of 2014, their last update to the game (not counting the testing updates that you can opt into, was in Jun of 2015. They did have some updates before then. They have been working on the game according to the opt in option. However, being one of the people who didn't opt into it, i wouldn't know what sort of ""testing"" is going on, and based off of the forum posts of actual testers... there doesn't appear to be that much to be impressed with. So, if you like the idea, and want to try to help out the devs... then by all means buy the game. But do so knowing that at this point in the development, you're taking a shot in the dark as to if there will be any sort of pay off (aka finished game) or not.I bought on the first day it was released onto Early Access. While I'm disappointed that i don't have much of a game yet to play, i do have hope and currently do not regert buying the game.I will update this review once the game has something to show for itself other than a tech demo style of game."
