,Not Recommended,305960,15295898,"Posted: 10 April, 2015",all,Enter,"Before you read this review, I ask that you know and understand that I was fully prepared to deal with any glitches, bugs, problems, or lack of content in this game, knowing that it is in early access and certain there was an idea here to be built upon. That said, I think I can firmly say that this game should not have been released into early access at this point in time as there is no central idea to build upon. Not only that, but there aren't any mechanics either. Flight is as about as smooth and simple as dancing the can-can with a pitchfork shoved firmly up your ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥, the graphics are about as appealing as the head of medusa if the snakes on her head suffered from projectile vomit, and I have to be incredibly careful where I fly lest I fly out of the flat world, where I ended up spending more than half of my time despite being more cautious than my mother on my first day of school. The ""goblins"" and ""people"" might as well have been dots on the screen, and the quite sparsely spread excuses for structures might have fallen over if I farted in the wrong direction- I'm not quite sure what I did, they were always falling over anyways. I can say, however, that the rest of the game was a blissful journey through neverland without feeling a sense of guilt that would have made hitler feel like a goody-two shoes, simply because there was no rest of the game. Perhaps with three more years of work it won't make Tōru Iwatani feel like his Pac-Man game was ages ahead of it's time. I don't think I've ever given up on a game as quickly as I gave up on this one for fear of losing my precious time that I might have spent better playing some other game."
