,Recommended,305960,21266474,"Posted: 16 February, 2016",all,Bird Enthusiast,"At this stage (being written as of 8.5), there are still bugs, but less than there was beforeSome oft these bugs may still exist, though, as i have yet to test them due to being stuck on the same maountainous world (more on that in bugs/issues). That being said, i'll leave past comments there, but they will be marked with ""(8.04)"" after them, and at the end of the section.Bugs/Issues---YOU CANNOT QUIT THE GAME NOMALLY ONCE YOU'RE IN. Once you're in the game, the pause menu only brings up the new tabs (dragon, grow, hoard) and the options of ""Resume,"" ""Respawn,"" ""Controls and Tips,"" and ""Options.""There is no option to quit.Looking at other screenshots of the game, all the menus are in the right places, but i think instead that it's the UI that isn't scaling correctly relative to the developer's resolution, resulting in either inaccesible or overlapping (or both) buttons.---If you choose to respawn, you'll be stuck at a loading screen for an indefinite amt of time (i sat at the loading screen after respawning for around 7 minutes)---Upon creating a dragon, no matter the kind, when looking at it in the selection screen, it will always show as a ""Drake, Green Dragon"" (the devs noted this in their update notes)---Even with the deletion of an old dragon and the creation of a new one, you still have the same hoard, the same stats, and spawn on the same map (regardless of which map you choose)---After picking my map for the first time, get used to it, because you will be stuck there FOREVER.-Even after reloading and selecting a different map, you will be sent to the same map you were just at.---The music/sound effects are quiet, and there are no volume options in the ""Options"" menu---You have to look directly at a target, so you don't know if it's dead or not (The only way i can tell is if the health ticker stops counting down, as well as the sound effects from said creature stopping)---there is no enemy health bar (which would be really useful)---enemies pile onto the center of your dragon, making them difficult, if not impossible to kill---trees still don't bleed---M3 (clicking the mousewheel) for tail bash doesn't work---what is M5? (for a fireball)---the funfacts at the loading screen pop by too fast to read it all accurately---you can't see the ""Play"" button on lower resolutions, but even on hiugher resolutions it is stacked under the ""Your Dragons"" button---Starving still has no consequence---having the ability to walk through small houses (8.04)---floating stuctures (8.04)But there are some good things!---eating is no longer instantaneous---the day and night cycle is excellent and pretty---there is now a health counter (for yourself, at least)---you can no longer fly off the edge of the map---the map is of colossal and realistic size---animations are very smooth---fun combat (even with enemies climbing onto you, lol)---you no longer fly up faster than you fly forward---scrolling up in the ""Grow"" menu reveals money! One gold unit is 65 actual gold into your hoard, instantly. Be rich!---Hunger now depletes at a rate relative to what you're doing (standing, running, flying), and at a much more reasonable rate---no more glitching water (8.04)---swimming! (though your head is underwater) (8.04)---the developer(s) makes almost *no* contact with their community. we don't know if it's still being worked on, and (i feel) we have little input on the next features to be implemented/bugs to fix~I've not entered any cave yet (as none have spawned for me in either the past version or the current one)~I've also not experimented with the effects of weight and armors on flying and combatIt's exactly what it says to be—Dragon The Game. It is also still in early access, and the bugs listed in the first portion are accaptable (for now). And, unlike many other early access games i've heard of, the devs are still working on it (and from what i can tell, progress will only be getting faster from here!)It's an excellent game with immeasurable potential, and things will only get better from here."
76561198072827864,Not Recommended,305960,14450389,"Posted: 13 February, 2015",all,dangeraaron10,"Feburary, 2015 was when I first gave this game a review.I gave it a thumbs up because it had potential.  Sadly I'm going to have to update this review, as of January 2017, and change it to a thumbs down only because I just remembered that I backed this disgrace on both Early Access and then on their (somehow successful) Kickstarter.I bought this game initially when it first crept onto Steam in Early Access form.  It was a little square of land floating in the endless void where you got to move around a shoddy looking dragon asset, fly around haphazardly and burn some villager and goblin assets.  Even then, in the most barebones, tech-demo-y existence of this game it was more playable then than it is now.  Let this sink in.Two years ago, the game was more stable than it is right now.These days, despite a few additions of enemies and ground textures, the game has made almost no positive changes.  But it has made changes.  Oh yes, the game's stability has actually degraded over the last year or so.  The dragon controls terribly, buttons simply do not work, commands are mapped to mouse buttons that don't exist on most commercial mice, enemies still try to kill you long after you killed or even ATE them, the game crashes frequently and such a simple looking game runs awful on even high end computers.Did I mention there was, or might still be, an achievement that's granted if you go into a cave lair and get stuck there?  Because that's acceptable.  The lair isn't there anymore, to my knowledge.There is nothing redeeming here.  There's no fun gameplay loop here.  It's a herculean effort just to get the game to work on your computer.The thing that really stings the most is the complete lack of communication from the developers to their EA Steam community.  Long bouts of silence broken up by non-updates if the community got too silent and goes so far as to childishly insult its concerned stakeholders because they are rightfully upset about the product they might have double-dipped funds into in hopes it would become their dream dragon game.I really wanted this game to be good.  I still do, in fact!  But honestly, if its incredibly small but incredibly dedicated fanbase tried, they could probably make a far better game in half the time.Pros?  Nothing.  Cons?  Everything.Avoid.  The Dragon Dream remains a dream, for now.This was my previous review in Feburary 2015:This game is very promising.  It's like a dragon egg starting to bump around and crack the shell.  From what I've seen of Red Level Games they seem to be passionate about the project and are using the funds they recieved already from Early Access to hire more people to their team.  Updates are oncoming and just had one recently to its beta client.  If you're looking for a finished game I obviously cannot reccomend it, but the game has a long way to go and the devs and players know it.  However, if you look at the money as an investment and you're really interested in seeing this project come into fruitation for the ultimate dragon game, then I'd give it a buy.Flying around burning stuff is fun in its own right.  I find myself logging on occaisionally to the live client just to torch some goblins or townsfolk, while also attempting to break the stamina bar in order to continuously accelerate in the air, flying at Mach 2 before crashing into a mountain.  All I can say is, as of right now it's a mildly fun but flawed dragon flight simulator with some objects to torch.  But I hope that this game sticks it out in the longrun."
